          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>Given two sets <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, a function from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> is a mapping that takes each element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  A]]></fr:tex> to a single element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>. <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[f:A\rightarrow  B]]></fr:tex></html:p>
            <html:p><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(x)]]></fr:tex> represents the element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> associated with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>.<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[B=\{y\in  B: y=f(x) \text { for some } x\in  A\}]]></fr:tex></html:p>
            <html:p>The domain of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is the set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>. The range of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is some subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, not necessarily equal to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
